00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:48.180
This afternoon's
program features

00:00:48.180 --> 00:00:52.320
Xu Bing, a prolific
and versatile artist

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:54.270
working at the
forefront of Chinese

00:00:54.270 --> 00:00:58.150
and global contemporary art.

00:00:58.150 --> 00:01:01.810
Xu has presented his work,
which includes mixed media

00:01:01.810 --> 00:01:04.690
installations,
prints, and sculptures

00:01:04.690 --> 00:01:08.900
and recently film at major
venues around the world,

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:11.540
including here at Harvard.

00:01:11.540 --> 00:01:15.650
I'm thrilled to welcome
Xu back to campus.

00:01:15.650 --> 00:01:19.390
In installations of often
all unsparing scale,

00:01:19.390 --> 00:01:23.620
Xu's art confronts us with the
instability of our perceptions

00:01:23.620 --> 00:01:25.270
and our assumptions.

00:01:25.270 --> 00:01:27.760
As it does so,
Xu's art addresses

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:29.560
some of the
fundamental challenges

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:31.810
of contemporary society--

00:01:31.810 --> 00:01:35.980
the precarious connections
between language and truth,

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:39.970
the difficulties of translation
across cultural and linguistic

00:01:39.970 --> 00:01:44.050
boundaries, and the status
of the image in an era

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:46.750
of omnipresent surveillance.

00:01:46.750 --> 00:01:51.070
Let me share just
a few examples.

00:01:51.070 --> 00:01:53.860
Perhaps Xu's most
iconic work is Book

00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:57.070
from the Sky, a monumental
installation that

00:01:57.070 --> 00:02:01.180
complicates the relationship
between tradition, authority,

00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:02.560
and meaning.

00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:05.680
This work earned Xu
international acclaim,

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:10.120
including a MacArthur
Foundation Genius award.

00:02:10.120 --> 00:02:13.890
Created over four years
and finished in 1991,

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:17.590
Book from the Sky features
books, hanging scrolls,

00:02:17.590 --> 00:02:20.140
and wall panels, all
of which Xu produced

00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:23.920
using traditional Chinese
block carving, typesetting,

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:26.620
and book binding techniques.

00:02:26.620 --> 00:02:29.980
While Book for the Sky
invites reading, no part of it

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:32.110
can actually be read.

00:02:32.110 --> 00:02:34.300
This is because the
text features thousands

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:37.780
of glyphs that closely
resemble Chinese characters

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:39.760
but have been carefully
designed to be

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:42.550
devoid of semantic meaning.

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:45.400
By drawing us in this
way, Book from the Sky

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:47.590
exposes the fragility
of perception

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:50.050
and of the written word itself.

00:02:50.050 --> 00:02:54.370
We're left to wonder how much
our habitual acts of reading

00:02:54.370 --> 00:03:00.580
and recognition rely only
on surface level appearance.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:04.180
Xu's art also addresses the
relationship between meaning

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:07.660
and translation and how a
work impacts one audience

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:10.160
differently from another.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:12.790
For example, in Square
Word Calligraphy,

00:03:12.790 --> 00:03:15.610
Xu developed a system
of creating pictograms

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:20.920
of written English words that
resemble Chinese characters.

00:03:20.920 --> 00:03:24.220
To English language
readers these pictograms

00:03:24.220 --> 00:03:28.450
appear indecipherable but are
perfectly readable upon closer

00:03:28.450 --> 00:03:30.040
inspection.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:32.980
By contrast to Chinese
readers, the characters

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:35.980
might seem legible
at first glance

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:39.760
but they are in
fact indecipherable.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:43.200
In another series of works
titled Background Story,

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.630
Xu explores recognition
and misrecognition

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:48.760
in visual traditions.

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:51.790
He presents what seem
to be traditional ink

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:55.660
paintings of landscapes, but
as viewers approach the works,

00:03:55.660 --> 00:03:58.570
they come to see
that each painting is

00:03:58.570 --> 00:04:01.990
in fact a shadow and light
box insulation created

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:07.110
from carefully arranged
trash and natural debris.

00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:12.650
And finally, Xu's reset feature
length film, Dragonfly Eyes,

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:16.910
which the Harvard film archive
screened yesterday evening,

00:04:16.910 --> 00:04:20.360
continues his career
long exploration

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:26.210
of meaning and perception
in a fascinating new format.

00:04:26.210 --> 00:04:29.510
In just a few minutes,
we'll hear directly from Xu.

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:31.520
He'll present brief
remarks and then

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:35.060
engage in a discussion with
two Harvard faculty members

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:38.930
on the full range of
his work, its impact

00:04:38.930 --> 00:04:43.550
on contemporary arts, and
the overarching question what

00:04:43.550 --> 00:04:46.480
counts as art today.

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:48.300
Throughout his
distinguished career,

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:52.240
shoos Xu has pushed boundaries
of what's considered fine art.

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:55.930
He's received numerous awards,
including the MacArthur Genius

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:58.660
Grant that I mentioned
earlier and a medal of arts

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:00.730
from the US State Department.

00:05:00.730 --> 00:05:04.600
Currently, he serves as a
professor at the Central Art

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:09.100
Academy of Fine Arts in Beijing
and as the Andrew DY Professor

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:12.580
at Large at Cornell University.

00:05:12.580 --> 00:05:14.950
Xu's conversation
partners this afternoon

00:05:14.950 --> 00:05:18.460
are Jennifer Roberts
and Eugene Wang.

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:20.950
Jennifer is the
Johnson-Kulukundis family

00:05:20.950 --> 00:05:23.890
faculty director of
arts here at Radcliffe

00:05:23.890 --> 00:05:26.470
and the Elizabeth
Cary Agassi professor

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:30.280
