- A lay Buddhist.

00:36:09.990 --> 00:36:13.659
A non-believer?

00:36:13.659 --> 00:36:38.510
[CRASH]

00:36:38.510 --> 00:36:57.452
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:36:57.452 --> 00:37:00.030
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:37:00.030 --> 00:37:04.910
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:37:04.910 --> 00:37:06.660
- This is a narrative
fiction film.

00:37:06.660 --> 00:37:09.510
And the film is 81 minutes long.

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:16.130
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:37:16.130 --> 00:37:18.830
- What's special about this
film is that every frame of it

00:37:18.830 --> 00:37:20.600
really happened.

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:27.200
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:37:27.200 --> 00:37:29.870
- It's different from any
fiction film that we have

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:31.250
watched before,
because fiction--

00:37:31.250 --> 00:37:34.210
all other fiction
films are fabricated.

00:37:34.210 --> 00:37:48.900
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.330
- So considering time,
maybe we should move on

00:37:51.330 --> 00:37:52.390
to the conversation.

00:37:52.390 --> 00:37:56.300
But it is true, in fact,
that all of my previous work

00:37:56.300 --> 00:38:00.660
has a very intimate relationship
with Dragonfly Eyes.

00:38:00.660 --> 00:38:15.130
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:38:15.130 --> 00:38:18.340
- This is I consider
an artwork of mine,

00:38:18.340 --> 00:38:22.080
and basically I use
the format of a film.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:41.420
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:38:41.420 --> 00:38:44.350
- So basically I like to--
this is what I like to do with

00:38:44.350 --> 00:38:44.850
my work.

00:38:44.850 --> 00:38:48.290
I like to work really
seriously doing something,

00:38:48.290 --> 00:38:50.600
and then what I'm
actually trying to say

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:53.670
is not actually the
thing that I made.

00:38:53.670 --> 00:39:00.240
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:00.240 --> 00:39:01.820
- For example, with
this film there's

00:39:01.820 --> 00:39:04.550
no way for us to really
judge is this a documentary

00:39:04.550 --> 00:39:07.320
or is this a narrative film.

00:39:07.320 --> 00:39:09.200
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:09.200 --> 00:39:12.700
- Because it's more
real than a documentary.

00:39:12.700 --> 00:39:19.244
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:19.244 --> 00:39:21.410
- Because with documentaries
what you're doing often

00:39:21.410 --> 00:39:24.386
is can you just repeat
what happened or you

00:39:24.386 --> 00:39:25.760
interview someone
or you say, oh,

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:27.635
can you walk through
that door one more time.

00:39:29.780 --> 00:39:31.580
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:31.580 --> 00:39:36.170
- So within that-- inherent
in that is an unrealness.

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:44.089
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:44.089 --> 00:39:45.630
- So we screened
that film yesterday.

00:39:45.630 --> 00:39:47.338
I'm sure everyone has
a lot of questions.

00:39:47.338 --> 00:39:49.497
So let's proceed on
to the discussion.

00:39:49.497 --> 00:39:50.330
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:39:50.330 --> 00:39:51.200
- Thank you.

00:39:51.200 --> 00:40:00.820
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:00.820 --> 00:40:09.550
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:40:09.550 --> 00:40:10.050
- Thank you.

00:40:10.050 --> 00:40:11.970
That was wonderful.

00:40:11.970 --> 00:40:15.360
Once again, thank you to
everyone for coming today.

00:40:17.920 --> 00:40:21.150
I want to extend a
very special thanks

00:40:21.150 --> 00:40:24.059
to Joy Chen who is our
translator and interpreter

00:40:24.059 --> 00:40:24.600
this evening.

00:40:24.600 --> 00:40:27.528
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:31.725 --> 00:40:35.220
As we've seen so
much of Xu Bing's art

00:40:35.220 --> 00:40:39.884
contends with complexities of
translation, so it's actually,

00:40:39.884 --> 00:40:41.550
I think, wonderful
that we have a chance

00:40:41.550 --> 00:40:44.460
to experience this
in an embodied way

00:40:44.460 --> 00:40:45.790
tonight in this discussion.

00:40:45.790 --> 00:40:47.910
So thank you so much, Joy.

00:40:47.910 --> 00:40:48.768
So we have about--

00:40:51.319 --> 00:40:52.860
why don't we ask
questions, and we'll

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:54.550
talk for about 15 or 20 minutes.

00:40:54.550 --> 00:40:58.860
And then we'll move to
questions from the audience.

00:40:58.860 --> 00:41:00.840
And maybe I'll start.

00:41:00.840 --> 00:41:03.510
Many of us are, I
think, still reeling

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:06.960
from the incredible screening
of Dragonfly Eyes last night

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:08.940
at the Harvard Film Archive.

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:11.610
And thanks to the Harvard
Film Archive and its director

00:41:11.610 --> 00:41:15.600
Haden Guest for arranging this.

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:20.920
I wanted to ask Xu if
you could say something

00:41:20.920 --> 00:41:28.130
about your discovery and use of
facial recognition technology

00:41:28.130 --> 00:41:30.440
in surveillance
video, which I imagine

00:41:30.440 --> 00:41:34.160
must have been extremely
important for you

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:36.590
both because so
much of your work

00:41:36.590 --> 00:41:40.460
seems to be about recognition
and the difficulty

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:45.110
of recognizing or that moment
when a form snaps into meaning

00:41:45.110 --> 00:41:48.020
in a particular reader
or viewer's mind.

00:41:48.020 --> 00:41:53.030
And that also so much of your
prior work has to do with,

00:41:53.030 --> 00:41:57.530
as you've put it, the
semiotic and schematic quality

00:41:57.530 --> 00:42:00.800
of Chinese art and images.

00:42:00.800 --> 00:42:02.300
And just yesterday
in the print room

00:42:02.300 --> 00:42:05.617
you had said that
in Chinese art,

00:42:05.617 --> 00:42:07.700
the character for a tree
and an image for the tree

00:42:07.700 --> 00:42:09.560
are the same.

00:42:09.560 --> 00:42:13.880
And throughout your film, we
have these video images that

00:42:13.880 --> 00:42:15.530
are being rapidly labeled--

00:42:15.530 --> 00:42:19.070
automatically labeled by
the recognition technology.

00:42:19.070 --> 00:42:21.590
So I wonder if you could just
talk a little bit about how

00:42:21.590 --> 00:42:24.260
you've used that, how
it came into the film,

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:25.645
and how it worked.

00:42:25.645 --> 00:43:09.800
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:43:09.800 --> 00:43:20.660
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:43:20.660 --> 00:43:23.500
- So it took about five years
for us to make this film,

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:25.970
and within these five years,
surveillance technology

00:43:25.970 --> 00:43:30.140
was continually, sort of,
improving and developing.

00:43:30.140 --> 00:43:37.040
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:43:37.040 --> 00:43:39.290
- So as an artist,
I really wanted

00:43:39.290 --> 00:43:43.550
to make sure that every frame we
used was surveillance footage.

00:43:43.550 --> 00:43:50.870
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:43:50.870 --> 00:43:55.220
- So you have the idea
that in two years, sort of,

00:43:55.220 --> 00:43:58.100
those devices in cars that
record what's happening

00:43:58.100 --> 00:44:00.160
within the car, those appeared.

00:44:00.160 --> 00:44:04.070
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:04.070 --> 00:44:06.140
- And then body
cams that cops wear.

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:07.830
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:07.830 --> 00:44:10.130
- Go Pro, the Go
Pro that you wear.

00:44:10.130 --> 00:44:13.819
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:13.819 --> 00:44:15.860
- And then with the advent
of these technologies,

00:44:15.860 --> 00:44:18.660
it changes our previous
conception of surveillance.

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:26.164
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:26.164 --> 00:44:27.830
- Because in the past,
surveillance was,

00:44:27.830 --> 00:44:29.510
kind of, stationary
in one place.

00:44:29.510 --> 00:44:32.372
But now surveillance moves
as well, moves with us.

00:44:32.372 --> 00:44:33.580
It has to do with our bodies.

00:44:33.580 --> 00:44:39.894
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:39.894 --> 00:44:41.810
- And then towards the
end, facial recognition

00:44:41.810 --> 00:44:44.030
developed very rapidly.

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:52.404
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:44:52.404 --> 00:44:53.820
- So you can see
that in our film,

00:44:53.820 --> 00:44:57.110
there are many layers,
different ways of treating

00:44:57.110 --> 00:44:58.849
this very complicated
phenomenon that's

00:44:58.849 --> 00:44:59.890
happening in our society.

00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:16.460
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:45:16.460 --> 00:45:19.252
- So it's almost like a Chinese
Theater or a Chinese drama.

00:45:19.252 --> 00:45:20.960
You have these twists
and turns, and it's

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:24.160
like using this technology
to try to parse out

00:45:24.160 --> 00:45:25.450
the different elements.

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:42.920
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:47.000
- So then that's why we
use this, sort of, square

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.610
and the search function and
then that is accompanied

00:45:49.610 --> 00:45:51.050
by a computer's voice.

00:45:51.050 --> 00:45:53.490
And this computer's
voice has a, sort of,

00:45:53.490 --> 00:45:55.310
a dumbed-down quality to it.

00:45:55.310 --> 00:46:00.150
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:46:00.150 --> 00:46:02.880
- So it says things
like man, woman, car.

00:46:02.880 --> 00:46:09.190
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:46:09.190 --> 00:46:11.570
- But we discovered that
this type of simplicity

00:46:11.570 --> 00:46:15.080
actually shares something
with classical Chinese poetry

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:15.935
or Japanese haikus.

00:46:22.630 --> 00:46:26.620
- OK, Xu Bing, welcome
back to the Harvard.

00:46:26.620 --> 00:46:28.180
You've been here
a number of times,

00:46:28.180 --> 00:46:32.230
and each time is a quite
meaningful experience.

00:46:32.230 --> 00:46:35.320
And so I want to just
take this occasion--

00:46:35.320 --> 00:46:38.170
it's such a rare occasion
where I have you,

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:41.620
one of the most celebrated
print-makers in the world,

00:46:41.620 --> 00:46:44.230
and also I have Jennifer
who studies prints

00:46:44.230 --> 00:46:46.750
and one of the eminent
scholar of print.

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:52.720
So it's a rare occasion
that I can use your own word

00:46:52.720 --> 00:46:57.340
to corner you or corner
your thinking to push you

00:46:57.340 --> 00:46:58.660
to the corner I think.

00:46:58.660 --> 00:47:01.330
So I know you.

00:47:01.330 --> 00:47:06.070
I follow your career,
and for decades, we've

00:47:06.070 --> 00:47:07.120
been old friends.

00:47:07.120 --> 00:47:10.540
And one thing I
often tell people

00:47:10.540 --> 00:47:15.403
is that as a print-maker,
Xu Bing is a control freak.

00:47:15.403 --> 00:47:17.926
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:29.740
You always want to make
sure that all the steps that

00:47:29.740 --> 00:47:32.590
lead to the final product
should not go wrong.

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:38.270
I remember you were
making that how

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:43.610
to have the cocoon spin
out web that can eventually

00:47:43.610 --> 00:47:45.020
cover a computer set.

00:47:48.160 --> 00:47:53.830
That has to involve ordering
certain kind of spring worms

00:47:53.830 --> 00:47:54.505
from Texas.

00:47:59.430 --> 00:48:03.990
They'll come-- they have to
arrive at a certain time,

00:48:03.990 --> 00:48:06.530
and the timing will be so
perfect so that they can spin.

00:48:09.130 --> 00:48:17.430
So knowing you with that kind
of control freak mentality, how

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:21.840
you have to work with
a medium that is--

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:24.310
could potential get out of hand.

00:48:27.690 --> 00:48:31.432
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:48:31.432 --> 00:48:36.870
Especially when this film
is a film without involving

00:48:36.870 --> 00:48:41.030
your team taking a single shot.

00:48:41.030 --> 00:48:44.980
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:48:44.980 --> 00:48:49.520
So I imagine that you would
like the fact that there

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:54.740
were emergent properties from
this medium or production

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:56.820
process.

00:48:56.820 --> 00:48:57.950
- That he likes--

00:48:57.950 --> 00:48:59.532
- Yeah, you like that fact.

00:48:59.532 --> 00:49:06.635
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:49:06.635 --> 00:49:12.950
And that in some ways is a
departure from your earlier

00:49:12.950 --> 00:49:15.686
printmaking self.

00:49:15.686 --> 00:49:21.225
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:49:21.225 --> 00:49:25.440
And also I found this
kind of intriguing

00:49:25.440 --> 00:49:30.600
that as a print-maker,
you use hand a lot.

00:49:30.600 --> 00:49:36.262
And now you let your hand idle.

00:49:36.262 --> 00:49:41.080
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:49:41.080 --> 00:49:43.840
Yesterday, we were in
the viewing session,

00:49:43.840 --> 00:49:49.480
and when you demonstrate how
the carvers work their wrist,

00:49:49.480 --> 00:49:53.140
your hand was dancing
in the air all the time.

00:49:53.140 --> 00:49:55.540
And that was quite
amazing movement.

00:49:55.540 --> 00:49:58.430
I can't help marveling at that.

00:49:58.430 --> 00:50:02.790
So now it's the eye taking over.

00:50:02.790 --> 00:50:04.130
Hand is idle.

00:50:06.680 --> 00:50:09.521
Do you feel a sense of loss?

00:50:09.521 --> 00:50:12.320
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:16.010
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:50:16.010 --> 00:50:18.080
- Very good question,
Professor Wang.

00:50:18.080 --> 00:50:26.900
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:50:26.900 --> 00:50:30.110
- So, in fact, I did go through
a very rigorous conservatory

00:50:30.110 --> 00:50:34.020
training, art school training.

00:50:34.020 --> 00:50:41.950
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:50:41.950 --> 00:50:45.670
- So my training in printmaking
was very helpful to me.

00:50:45.670 --> 00:50:59.390
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:50:59.390 --> 00:51:02.670
- Because printmaking is a
very indirect form of art.

00:51:02.670 --> 00:51:06.020
So it requires a lot
of control to break

00:51:06.020 --> 00:51:08.380
through the limitations
of the form.

00:51:08.380 --> 00:51:19.310
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:51:19.310 --> 00:51:22.170
- So if you're not
particular about every step,

00:51:22.170 --> 00:51:25.920
then the end result
will be just a mess.

00:51:25.920 --> 00:51:33.690
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:51:33.690 --> 00:51:35.810
- But I have a
personal preference,

00:51:35.810 --> 00:51:40.170
which is that I like to do
things that are challenging.

00:51:40.170 --> 00:51:43.260
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:51:43.260 --> 00:51:45.870
- If it's something that anyone
can do or everyone can do,

00:51:45.870 --> 00:51:48.110
then it's not worth me doing it.

00:51:48.110 --> 00:51:57.020
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:51:57.020 --> 00:51:59.890
- So even works like
the silkworm work

00:51:59.890 --> 00:52:01.880
that you mentioned,
it looks like it's

00:52:01.880 --> 00:52:03.320
very, sort of, spontaneous.

00:52:03.320 --> 00:52:06.230
But actually it
acquired a lot of work.

00:52:06.230 --> 00:52:10.709
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:52:10.709 --> 00:52:12.500
- Because we had to
control it so that when

00:52:12.500 --> 00:52:14.450
the exhibit opened,
these silk worms

00:52:14.450 --> 00:52:16.270
are actually spinning silk.

00:52:16.270 --> 00:52:22.640
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:26.690
- But every type or species
of silkworm when it starts

00:52:26.690 --> 00:52:28.380
producing silk, it's different.

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:47.820
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:49.200
- So what did we do?

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:52.400
We had to order first a
specific species of silkworms

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:54.990
and then actually feed
them and let them grow

00:52:54.990 --> 00:52:58.490
and then record when they start
producing silk and all of that.

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:03.760
And then use that
to do the work.

00:53:03.760 --> 00:53:27.730
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:53:27.730 --> 00:53:29.880
- So I've exhibited
all over the world,

00:53:29.880 --> 00:53:33.690
and basically what people say
about me is I'm too picky.

00:53:33.690 --> 00:53:36.500
Because basically, if I
go into an installation

00:53:36.500 --> 00:53:38.135
and I don't feel
right in the space,

00:53:38.135 --> 00:53:39.885
then I go back and
check the measurements.

00:53:39.885 --> 00:53:45.740
Then definitely it's always true
that they didn't adhere exactly

00:53:45.740 --> 00:53:47.210
to the measurements.

00:53:47.210 --> 00:53:55.816
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:53:55.816 --> 00:53:57.690
- So to a lot of people
maybe they would say,

00:53:57.690 --> 00:53:59.260
oh, it's just a little
bit of a difference.

00:53:59.260 --> 00:54:00.009
It doesn't matter.

00:54:00.009 --> 00:54:05.100
But to me, it effects the
overall effect of the work.

00:54:05.100 --> 00:54:12.532
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:54:12.532 --> 00:54:16.170
- So actually Dragonfly
Eyes has a, sort of,

00:54:16.170 --> 00:54:20.950
internal connection to my
previous printmaking work.

00:54:20.950 --> 00:54:31.900
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:54:31.900 --> 00:54:33.880
- So it's about
taking this limit--

00:54:33.880 --> 00:54:36.610
a limitation and
then transforming it

00:54:36.610 --> 00:54:37.670
into something special.

00:54:43.140 --> 00:54:44.640
- We have just a
couple more minutes

00:54:44.640 --> 00:54:46.950
before we move to the audience.

00:54:46.950 --> 00:54:50.415
Perhaps, a good final
question from us

00:54:50.415 --> 00:54:54.780
would be just to ask you
where you see your work going

00:54:54.780 --> 00:54:59.730
now and in the future and about
how Dragonfly Eyes has perhaps

00:54:59.730 --> 00:55:01.542
changed the trajectory
of your work.

00:55:04.140 --> 00:55:15.080
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:55:15.080 --> 00:55:23.710
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:55:23.710 --> 00:55:27.600
- You can see that my work
takes a lot of different forms,

00:55:27.600 --> 00:55:29.830
and that's because
I don't really

00:55:29.830 --> 00:55:33.130
take art style that seriously.

00:55:33.130 --> 00:55:42.520
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:55:42.520 --> 00:55:44.910
- Because I want to say
something no one's said before.

00:55:44.910 --> 00:55:47.680
And if I want to say it in
a proper way and a way that

00:55:47.680 --> 00:55:52.040
really gets at it, it has
to be in an interesting way.

00:55:52.040 --> 00:56:02.400
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:56:02.400 --> 00:56:05.110
- And the formats and
styles that the old masters

00:56:05.110 --> 00:56:08.260
used, for example, to
express their ideas, that

00:56:08.260 --> 00:56:11.470
was particular to their time
and what they wanted to say.

00:56:11.470 --> 00:56:18.580
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:56:18.580 --> 00:56:22.040
- Including my own artistic
language from my older works,

00:56:22.040 --> 00:56:26.510
I can't just co-op that
into my current work either.

00:56:26.510 --> 00:56:39.900
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:56:39.900 --> 00:56:43.360
- Because to me my art has
to do with your sensitivity

00:56:43.360 --> 00:56:48.850
to the present moment and
then how you take old forms

00:56:48.850 --> 00:56:51.460
and transform that using
your current sensitivity

00:56:51.460 --> 00:56:53.930
to the contemporary society.

00:56:53.930 --> 00:57:10.440
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:57:10.440 --> 00:57:13.530
- And it's necessarily the
case that contemporary society,

00:57:13.530 --> 00:57:17.620
the way things are right now
within that there is more--

00:57:17.620 --> 00:57:21.600
there are more avenues for
creativity and the more

00:57:21.600 --> 00:57:24.320
inspiration can be found
in the present moment.

00:57:24.320 --> 00:57:33.930
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:57:33.930 --> 00:57:37.850
- So regarding what I'm doing
next, actually, I don't know.

00:57:37.850 --> 00:57:41.890
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:57:41.890 --> 00:57:44.970
- But I trust that I
have something to say.

00:57:44.970 --> 00:57:50.326
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:57:50.326 --> 00:57:52.200
- Because this world is
changing too quickly.

00:57:52.200 --> 00:57:56.440
There are too many questions
that need us-- need answers.

00:57:56.440 --> 00:58:00.330
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:58:00.330 --> 00:58:02.810
- To me, art is not something
you get from planning.

00:58:05.650 --> 00:58:07.680
- Very good.

00:58:07.680 --> 00:58:13.870
OK, the magic microphone is
coming up to the center aisle.

00:58:13.870 --> 00:58:17.260
I wanted to-- we want to
open the floor to about 15

00:58:17.260 --> 00:58:20.266
or 20 minutes of questions.

00:58:20.266 --> 00:58:22.390
I know many of you were at
the screening last night

00:58:22.390 --> 00:58:25.640
and may have
questions about that.

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:27.430
If you do have a
question for Xu Bing,

00:58:27.430 --> 00:58:30.740
please come up to
the microphone here.

00:58:30.740 --> 00:58:35.260
And please identify yourself
prior to asking your question.

00:58:35.260 --> 00:58:37.980
And we'll have questions for
15 minutes or so and then

00:58:37.980 --> 00:58:39.070
a reception downstairs.

00:58:39.070 --> 00:58:39.770
- No problem.

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:42.070
My name is Claribel Santiago.

00:58:42.070 --> 00:58:46.150
When you lived in New York
and you witnessed personally

00:58:46.150 --> 00:58:50.710
your journey of
9/11 and you said

00:58:50.710 --> 00:58:54.730
that changed you as an artist,
did that change you to--

00:58:54.730 --> 00:58:59.200
now to just focus--

00:58:59.200 --> 00:59:06.640
not focused, but now look for
the pain of others in your art

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:07.860
now?

00:59:07.860 --> 00:59:17.210
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:59:17.210 --> 00:59:23.770
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:59:23.770 --> 00:59:25.630
- So actually at the
time I witnessed--

00:59:25.630 --> 00:59:29.070
I saw with my own eyes
the twin towers falling.

00:59:29.070 --> 00:59:35.890
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:59:35.890 --> 00:59:40.840
- But actually what I thought
of in the moment was the scene

00:59:40.840 --> 00:59:43.590
on Chang'an Street on June 4th--

00:59:43.590 --> 00:59:45.690
the June 4th incident.

00:59:45.690 --> 00:59:51.070
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

00:59:51.070 --> 00:59:52.870
- And in that moment,
I thought, wow,

00:59:52.870 --> 00:59:56.357
from this moment on this world
is really going to change.

00:59:56.357 --> 01:00:02.040
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:05.050
- Because when we left
Beijing back then, we had--

01:00:05.050 --> 01:00:07.220
back then Beijing wasn't safe.

01:00:07.220 --> 01:00:12.400
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:00:12.400 --> 01:00:16.000
- And now New York has become
a place that isn't safe.

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:32.176
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:00:32.176 --> 01:00:33.550
- But what really
impacted me was

01:00:33.550 --> 01:00:36.580
when I walked out of my
building the next day,

01:00:36.580 --> 01:00:41.680
I felt like the entire
balance of the ecosystem was--

01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:44.440
it was all array, because
suddenly these two

01:00:44.440 --> 01:00:46.460
big buildings were not there.

01:00:46.460 --> 01:00:55.420
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:00:55.420 --> 01:00:58.750
- There was an article, a
report then also of a parent

01:00:58.750 --> 01:01:01.810
telling their child, oh, if you
can't find your way home just

01:01:01.810 --> 01:01:03.170
look for the twin towers.

01:01:03.170 --> 01:01:05.410
And with that, you'll be
able to find your way home.

01:01:05.410 --> 01:01:11.830
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:01:11.830 --> 01:01:13.360
- But faced with
such an incident,

01:01:13.360 --> 01:01:15.896
you really don't
know what to do.

01:01:15.896 --> 01:01:25.640
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:28.310
- But because I have this habit
of collecting raw materials,

01:01:28.310 --> 01:01:31.472
so then I went down to the
site and collected some dust.

01:01:31.472 --> 01:01:32.930
But actually at
that time, I didn't

01:01:32.930 --> 01:01:34.138
know what I would do with it.

01:01:39.450 --> 01:02:10.339
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:02:10.339 --> 01:02:12.130
- Would you like to
translate her question?

01:02:12.130 --> 01:02:15.880
Summarize what she asked so that
the audience know what you--

01:02:15.880 --> 01:02:17.127
your question.

01:02:17.127 --> 01:02:19.929
[SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:02:19.929 --> 01:02:23.170
- So her question is
about why he didn't

01:02:23.170 --> 01:02:25.225
include a particular work.

01:02:25.225 --> 01:02:28.000
The English title is
like the-- is it utopia?

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:29.390
No, it's the--

01:02:29.390 --> 01:02:31.690
It's the peach
blossom, but it's--

01:02:31.690 --> 01:02:33.880
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:02:33.880 --> 01:02:36.520
- Anyway, her question
was why did you not

01:02:36.520 --> 01:02:39.905
include that work in
your introduction today.

01:02:39.905 --> 01:02:42.280
Is it, because you don't see
it as being in the same vein

01:02:42.280 --> 01:02:44.990
as the other works.

01:02:44.990 --> 01:02:52.890
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:02:52.890 --> 01:02:54.410
- So I actually have a lot--

01:02:54.410 --> 01:02:57.850
I have produced a lot of work,
so I already went over time.

01:02:57.850 --> 01:03:02.940
So it wasn't possible
to include everything.

01:03:02.940 --> 01:03:04.190
- So, hi, how are you?

01:03:04.190 --> 01:03:07.520
So welcome to Harvard,
and I actually

01:03:07.520 --> 01:03:09.650
saw your exhibition
in Metropolitan

01:03:09.650 --> 01:03:11.490
and also in Beijing.

01:03:11.490 --> 01:03:13.430
I was really honored
to have you here.

01:03:13.430 --> 01:03:19.580
And my question is in China
actually the freedom of speech

01:03:19.580 --> 01:03:22.980
become a little bit more
restrict in the recent years.

01:03:22.980 --> 01:03:26.510
And as an artist,
artist want to be free

01:03:26.510 --> 01:03:29.430
and want to have the freedom
to do whatever they want to do.

01:03:29.430 --> 01:03:32.330
But when you are
approaching your art,

01:03:32.330 --> 01:03:35.422
how do you have that
consideration when

01:03:35.422 --> 01:03:36.630
you are approaching your art?

01:03:36.630 --> 01:03:40.580
Would you like
modify it in some way

01:03:40.580 --> 01:03:45.750
or soften the stand you
have in your art work.

01:03:45.750 --> 01:03:49.490
The second question
is your attitude

01:03:49.490 --> 01:03:54.560
to or your evaluation of Ai
Weiwei, which is a very--

01:03:54.560 --> 01:03:59.840
like a political artist
and what's your attitude

01:03:59.840 --> 01:04:03.680
to his art work and his career.

01:04:03.680 --> 01:04:04.320
Thank you.

01:04:07.960 --> 01:04:17.090
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:04:17.090 --> 01:04:21.470
- So it's true that China is a
very political kind of society.

01:04:21.470 --> 01:04:24.480
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:04:24.480 --> 01:04:28.070
- But actually America
is that way too.

01:04:28.070 --> 01:04:42.420
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:04:42.420 --> 01:04:44.600
- So as an artist, even
if you're not directly

01:04:44.600 --> 01:04:48.120
dealing with political
things in your work,

01:04:48.120 --> 01:04:51.200
it's always inevitable that
you have this undercurrent

01:04:51.200 --> 01:04:53.480
of politics in your work.

01:04:53.480 --> 01:05:04.686
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:05:04.686 --> 01:05:06.940
- So every artist has a
different personality,

01:05:06.940 --> 01:05:11.460
and for example, Ai Weiwei is
a more direct kind of person.

01:05:11.460 --> 01:05:14.464
So he's-- he'll deal with issues
more directly, and he'll--

01:05:14.464 --> 01:05:16.130
he's the type of
person who wants to get

01:05:16.130 --> 01:05:18.210
into a fight with you directly.

01:05:18.210 --> 01:05:22.170
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:05:22.170 --> 01:05:25.010
- But other artists have other
personalities where maybe you

01:05:25.010 --> 01:05:28.750
want to deal with problems in
a other way-- in another way.

01:05:28.750 --> 01:05:30.990
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:05:30.990 --> 01:05:34.960
- So it's just different.

01:05:34.960 --> 01:05:36.550
- Hi, my name's Kalis.

01:05:36.550 --> 01:05:39.770
Thank you Xu Bing for coming to
Harvard and giving this talk.

01:05:39.770 --> 01:05:42.986
My question is what do you think
this movie-- or what are your--

01:05:42.986 --> 01:05:44.860
what are your thoughts
on what this movie has

01:05:44.860 --> 01:05:48.010
to say about contemporary
Chinese society.

01:05:48.010 --> 01:05:50.497
And like I know it
probably couldn't

01:05:50.497 --> 01:05:52.330
be made in the United
States, and if it was,

01:05:52.330 --> 01:05:53.270
it would be very different.

01:05:53.270 --> 01:05:54.940
But what do you think
about this movie

01:05:54.940 --> 01:05:58.240
makes it uniquely Chinese
and exemplifying something

01:05:58.240 --> 01:05:59.740
about contemporary
society in China.

01:06:02.290 --> 01:06:11.160
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:06:11.160 --> 01:06:13.190
- So actually the
target for this movie

01:06:13.190 --> 01:06:16.690
Dragonfly Eyes is
the entire world.

01:06:16.690 --> 01:06:23.330
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:06:23.330 --> 01:06:24.830
- Because actually
our world today

01:06:24.830 --> 01:06:30.460
has become a gigantic
camera studio.

01:06:30.460 --> 01:06:35.660
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:06:35.660 --> 01:06:37.850
- It's a lot like
the social imaginings

01:06:37.850 --> 01:06:41.180
that we found in
The Truman Show.

01:06:43.970 --> 01:06:50.300
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:51.800
- So in this film,
I actually didn't

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:55.020
want to directly talk
about surveillance.

01:06:55.020 --> 01:07:07.640
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:07:07.640 --> 01:07:11.220
- Because the very fact
that someone can take solely

01:07:11.220 --> 01:07:13.220
surveillance footage and
make a narrative film--

01:07:13.220 --> 01:07:17.420
and make a film out of it, that
already says something about

01:07:17.420 --> 01:07:19.760
the state of our society.

01:07:19.760 --> 01:07:27.240
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:07:27.240 --> 01:07:30.770
- And I didn't want
to directly talk

01:07:30.770 --> 01:07:34.394
about this kind
of Orwellian 1984.

01:07:34.394 --> 01:07:40.550
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:07:40.550 --> 01:07:42.940
- Because to me this type
of concept everyone knows.

01:07:42.940 --> 01:07:46.650
So there is-- it's not
necessary to talk about it.

01:07:46.650 --> 01:07:55.140
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:07:55.140 --> 01:07:57.140
- But to me what I
wanted to express

01:07:57.140 --> 01:07:59.330
was that to me actually
we've already entered

01:07:59.330 --> 01:08:01.850
into a post surveillance era.

01:08:01.850 --> 01:08:13.220
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:08:13.220 --> 01:08:17.090
- Because at least in China,
most of the surveillance--

01:08:17.090 --> 01:08:19.790
the footage that's being
taken, it's all been controlled

01:08:19.790 --> 01:08:23.250
by private companies
as well as individuals.

01:08:23.250 --> 01:08:31.340
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:08:31.340 --> 01:08:33.620
- So actually 99 % percent
of the footage that you see

01:08:33.620 --> 01:08:35.990
in this film, it's all
stuff that was uploaded

01:08:35.990 --> 01:08:38.710
by individuals or by
these private companies.

01:08:38.710 --> 01:08:52.310
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:08:52.310 --> 01:08:55.430
- So actually, the use
of surveillance footage

01:08:55.430 --> 01:08:59.240
has really expanded into
the individual's hands,

01:08:59.240 --> 01:09:04.000
and it has gone way beyond
what Orwell imagined in 1984.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:14.870
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:09:14.870 --> 01:09:17.300
- But actually this is
something that most people don't

01:09:17.300 --> 01:09:19.460
recognize, and actually
this is what I wanted

01:09:19.460 --> 01:09:21.578
to talk about in the film.

01:09:25.310 --> 01:10:04.550
- [SPEAKING CHINESE] So my
question is how do you define

01:10:04.550 --> 01:10:07.280
the relationship and the
connection between painting

01:10:07.280 --> 01:10:08.220
and words?

01:10:08.220 --> 01:10:10.182
Thank you.

01:10:10.182 --> 01:10:17.550
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:10:17.550 --> 01:10:20.870
- So in China it's true that
words and images have a very

01:10:20.870 --> 01:10:21.920
special relationship.

01:10:21.920 --> 01:10:26.400
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:10:26.400 --> 01:10:28.350
- So you write the
character for mountain

01:10:28.350 --> 01:10:31.570
and you're actually
painting a mountain as well.

01:10:31.570 --> 01:10:48.339
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:10:48.339 --> 01:10:50.630
- So it seems that these days
young people what they're

01:10:50.630 --> 01:10:54.170
looking for is a very
direct, a very simple way

01:10:54.170 --> 01:10:56.720
of communicating--

01:10:56.720 --> 01:10:59.510
a way of communicating that
doesn't require much learning

01:10:59.510 --> 01:11:00.620
preferably.

01:11:00.620 --> 01:11:17.915
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:11:17.915 --> 01:11:21.410
- So for example, the Book
from the Ground, actually,

01:11:21.410 --> 01:11:24.860
I had the idea for this
work about 16, 17 years ago.

01:11:24.860 --> 01:11:28.350
But at the time not
enough emojis and icons

01:11:28.350 --> 01:11:30.930
existed to make it.

01:11:30.930 --> 01:11:43.210
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:11:43.210 --> 01:11:45.620
- So this type of thing
developed very quickly,

01:11:45.620 --> 01:11:47.720
and to a certain
extent, you could

01:11:47.720 --> 01:11:50.330
say that it really is
replacing traditional language,

01:11:50.330 --> 01:11:51.120
traditional words.

01:11:51.120 --> 01:11:58.940
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:11:58.940 --> 01:12:01.160
- So you can say that
the icons that you

01:12:01.160 --> 01:12:03.390
find in Book from the
Ground, they really do

01:12:03.390 --> 01:12:06.738
possess a very strong
language element to them.

01:12:12.550 --> 01:12:14.660
- Xu Bing, thank you
very much for being here.

01:12:14.660 --> 01:12:15.760
It's an honor.

01:12:15.760 --> 01:12:17.890
My name is Paula Billups.

01:12:17.890 --> 01:12:22.840
You spoke in your
talk about the garden

01:12:22.840 --> 01:12:27.460
that an artist builds around
themselves so that eventually

01:12:27.460 --> 01:12:29.530
you find that you're
surrounded by your work

01:12:29.530 --> 01:12:31.120
and that the past
and the present

01:12:31.120 --> 01:12:34.900
begin to speak to each other.

01:12:34.900 --> 01:12:37.390
Now that you're
furthering your career

01:12:37.390 --> 01:12:38.470
and you're on the other--

01:12:38.470 --> 01:12:41.560
you're on maybe in
the middle of that,

01:12:41.560 --> 01:12:46.990
do you feel that you can
predict what you're yet older

01:12:46.990 --> 01:12:49.220
self will be saying to you now?

01:12:49.220 --> 01:12:50.890
Are you still having
those conversations

01:12:50.890 --> 01:12:53.150
between past and present?

01:12:53.150 --> 01:12:57.370
How do you view that sense
of garden, that sense

01:12:57.370 --> 01:12:59.307
of the circle around you?

01:13:03.283 --> 01:13:06.490
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:13:06.490 --> 01:13:10.400
- In fact, this type of
feeling of speaking to yourself

01:13:10.400 --> 01:13:12.350
is strengthened.

01:13:12.350 --> 01:13:20.380
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:13:20.380 --> 01:13:22.570
- So actually the
cultural DNA that everyone

01:13:22.570 --> 01:13:26.370
possesses with them is
very deeply embedded.

01:13:26.370 --> 01:13:28.590
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:13:28.590 --> 01:13:30.700
- But when you need
it, it emerges.

01:13:30.700 --> 01:13:33.832
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:13:33.832 --> 01:13:35.540
- Sometimes it emerges,
and it helps you.

01:13:35.540 --> 01:13:37.460
Sometimes it's harmful to you.

01:13:37.460 --> 01:14:03.700
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:14:03.700 --> 01:14:07.141
- So it's like, for example,
in my wood block work earlier,

01:14:07.141 --> 01:14:09.766
printing work, I realized that
I was really interested in this,

01:14:09.766 --> 01:14:11.920
sort of, the layout of
the earth and the way

01:14:11.920 --> 01:14:13.667
you organize things.

01:14:13.667 --> 01:14:16.000
And then I realized that was
because during the Cultural

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:19.810
Revolution I was involved a
lot of the layout of newspapers

01:14:19.810 --> 01:14:20.560
and magazines.

01:14:24.170 --> 01:14:34.240
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:14:34.240 --> 01:14:39.100
- So it's more like my work now,
that's the way through which I

01:14:39.100 --> 01:14:42.790
look at my past and say, oh, so
actually those elements already

01:14:42.790 --> 01:14:43.960
existed back then.

01:14:43.960 --> 01:14:47.030
But I only know-- recognize it
like through my current work.

01:14:47.030 --> 01:14:55.235
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:14:55.235 --> 01:14:58.840
- So actually in a way what
an artist ends up doing,

01:14:58.840 --> 01:15:01.040
it's kind of faded in a way.

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:02.710
There's a faded quality to it.

01:15:02.710 --> 01:15:03.710
There's a destiny to it.

01:15:03.710 --> 01:15:11.150
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:15:11.150 --> 01:15:13.570
- So for example, say I really
like a certain style, not

01:15:13.570 --> 01:15:14.625
my style.

01:15:14.625 --> 01:15:16.750
But if that's not-- it that
does not belong to you,

01:15:16.750 --> 01:15:20.190
no matter how hard you work
at it it's not going to work.

01:15:20.190 --> 01:15:22.570
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:15:22.570 --> 01:15:25.126
- What belongs to you even
if you try to throw it away,

01:15:25.126 --> 01:15:26.160
it won't go.

01:15:26.160 --> 01:15:34.330
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:15:34.330 --> 01:15:36.220
- Like when I was
making Book from the Sky

01:15:36.220 --> 01:15:38.110
I really wanted
to make something

01:15:38.110 --> 01:15:42.300
that would be in alignment
with contemporary Western art.

01:15:42.300 --> 01:15:46.510
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:15:46.510 --> 01:15:49.440
- Because I wanted to escape
from our socialist art.

01:15:49.440 --> 01:15:54.940
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:15:54.940 --> 01:15:57.990
- But to go into a new art form,
I didn't know what that was.

01:15:57.990 --> 01:16:09.012
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:16:09.012 --> 01:16:10.720
- And under those
circumstances, what you

01:16:10.720 --> 01:16:14.840
end up producing is the most
real expression of who you are.

01:16:20.490 --> 01:16:22.600
- Hi, thank you for coming.

01:16:22.600 --> 01:16:25.170
My name's Indigo [INAUDIBLE],,
and I saw your Phoenixes

01:16:25.170 --> 01:16:26.710
in New York about
five years ago.

01:16:26.710 --> 01:16:28.410
And it's one of the
things that, like,

01:16:28.410 --> 01:16:30.830
really just kind of blew
me away at the time.

01:16:30.830 --> 01:16:33.036
And I think the
thing that I'm really

01:16:33.036 --> 01:16:34.410
interested in in
all of your work

01:16:34.410 --> 01:16:36.660
is the labor that goes
into it that I think

01:16:36.660 --> 01:16:39.750
it's almost like hidden
by how put together

01:16:39.750 --> 01:16:41.380
and how complete they are.

01:16:41.380 --> 01:16:44.042
And I really wanted to know
what your, like, values

01:16:44.042 --> 01:16:46.500
were in regards to that labor
and how it's, kind of, become

01:16:46.500 --> 01:16:48.720
a vehicle for the
content and the ways

01:16:48.720 --> 01:16:51.422
in which you conceptualize
that in your work.

01:16:51.422 --> 01:16:53.250
Thank you.

01:16:53.250 --> 01:16:56.390
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:16:56.390 --> 01:17:16.000
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:19.000
- So I always require
that in all of my works

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:22.830
the core concept has
to be very sturdy.

01:17:22.830 --> 01:17:28.726
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:17:28.726 --> 01:17:30.850
- And once that's clear,
the core concept is clear,

01:17:30.850 --> 01:17:34.340
then you have to give it
your all to realize it.

01:17:34.340 --> 01:18:02.020
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:18:02.020 --> 01:18:05.110
- So like Professor Wang
mentioned earlier about

01:18:05.110 --> 01:18:08.650
how with this new work the
hand, kind of, lays idle.

01:18:08.650 --> 01:18:11.140
But actually it's just a
different type of labor.

01:18:11.140 --> 01:18:13.250
It just requires maybe
the hand is not moving,

01:18:13.250 --> 01:18:15.850
but it requires a large
amount of labor as well.

01:18:15.850 --> 01:18:23.080
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:18:23.080 --> 01:18:25.160
- So for-- in order
to make this film,

01:18:25.160 --> 01:18:31.000
we downloaded 11,000
hours of footage.

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:41.750
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:18:41.750 --> 01:18:43.360
- Because this
type of technique,

01:18:43.360 --> 01:18:44.960
no one has ever used it before.

01:18:44.960 --> 01:18:46.200
So we really just--

01:18:46.200 --> 01:18:48.130
we didn't know how
to go about it.

01:18:48.130 --> 01:19:00.670
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:19:00.670 --> 01:19:04.810
- But I trusted that
within this mass volume

01:19:04.810 --> 01:19:07.020
of data that was being
collected locally

01:19:07.020 --> 01:19:10.290
that we would be able to find
what we needed to tell a story.

01:19:10.290 --> 01:19:28.360
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:19:28.360 --> 01:19:29.950
- So in the beginning,
it was almost

01:19:29.950 --> 01:19:31.450
like we were creating libraries.

01:19:31.450 --> 01:19:34.630
So we were categorizing things
by like a temple and then

01:19:34.630 --> 01:19:36.680
big temple, small
temple, northern temple,

01:19:36.680 --> 01:19:38.740
southern temple, oh, two
monks walking this way,

01:19:38.740 --> 01:19:40.014
three monks walking that way.

01:19:40.014 --> 01:19:41.680
And we categorized
everything like that,

01:19:41.680 --> 01:19:44.230
because we didn't know what
footage we would need yet.

01:19:44.230 --> 01:20:16.000
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:19.360
- So in the process of making
the film it was a continuous

01:20:19.360 --> 01:20:22.529
back and forth between the
editors and the screenwriters,

01:20:22.529 --> 01:20:24.820
because sometimes you-- the
screenwriters have a really

01:20:24.820 --> 01:20:27.137
great idea but you can't
find the material for it.

01:20:27.137 --> 01:20:28.720
And sometimes the
editor will discover

01:20:28.720 --> 01:20:30.680
something that
wasn't in the script

01:20:30.680 --> 01:20:32.960
but that's really interesting.

01:20:32.960 --> 01:20:46.555
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:20:46.555 --> 01:20:49.670
- So at the end when the
story was almost complete,

01:20:49.670 --> 01:20:51.010
we were missing one shot.

01:20:51.010 --> 01:20:56.200
And this one shot was shot of
a rainy night on a mountainside

01:20:56.200 --> 01:20:58.210
and you see a car
driving by, but we

01:20:58.210 --> 01:21:00.380
couldn't find this footage.

01:21:00.380 --> 01:21:02.530
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:21:02.530 --> 01:21:04.620
- So first we had to check
the weather forecast.

01:21:04.620 --> 01:21:06.200
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:21:06.200 --> 01:21:07.700
- Where is it going
to rain tonight?

01:21:07.700 --> 01:21:18.460
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:21:18.460 --> 01:21:19.990
- So we'd work for
so long that we

01:21:19.990 --> 01:21:22.550
knew where we would be able
to find that sort of image,

01:21:22.550 --> 01:21:25.120
and so we focused on
that particular spot

01:21:25.120 --> 01:21:26.920
and waited to see
if did it really--

01:21:26.920 --> 01:21:28.753
every morning, like,
did it rain that night?

01:21:28.753 --> 01:21:30.430
Did a car pass by?

01:21:30.430 --> 01:21:32.200
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:21:32.200 --> 01:21:34.330
- And this requires
a lot of labor.

01:21:36.950 --> 01:21:39.880
- OK, I think we have time
for one more short question,

01:21:39.880 --> 01:21:41.290
and then we'll move on.

01:21:41.290 --> 01:21:43.050
- I'll keep it short.

01:21:43.050 --> 01:22:17.650
- [SPEAKING CHINESE] So my
question was there are a lot

01:22:17.650 --> 01:22:19.650
of intersection between
commercial opportunities

01:22:19.650 --> 01:22:21.240
and art in China.

01:22:21.240 --> 01:22:23.400
Art is not only limited
to galleries anymore,

01:22:23.400 --> 01:22:28.950
but art are in shopping malls
and other commercial spaces.

01:22:28.950 --> 01:22:33.980
So I'm just wondering what are
Xu Bing's thoughts on that.

01:22:33.980 --> 01:22:47.880
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:22:47.880 --> 01:22:49.680
- Art has a lot of
different functions.

01:22:49.680 --> 01:22:52.430
So sometimes it's
to beautify a space,

01:22:52.430 --> 01:22:56.670
and sometimes it
can be a commodity.

01:22:56.670 --> 01:23:11.140
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:23:11.140 --> 01:23:13.610
- So sometimes I think
why is it that I'm

01:23:13.610 --> 01:23:15.440
able to sell my artwork?

01:23:15.440 --> 01:23:16.820
Why are collectors interested?

01:23:16.820 --> 01:23:18.500
I mean, really, like,
a lot of my works

01:23:18.500 --> 01:23:21.060
are just a bunch of scraps.

01:23:21.060 --> 01:23:41.900
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:23:41.900 --> 01:23:44.630
- But then I think maybe
what they're collecting,

01:23:44.630 --> 01:23:47.750
what museums and collectors
are collecting is that--

01:23:47.750 --> 01:23:51.650
is the special kind of concept
or way of thinking that is

01:23:51.650 --> 01:23:54.110
expressed through my artwork.

01:23:54.110 --> 01:24:13.950
- [SPEAKING CHINESE]

01:24:13.950 --> 01:24:17.540
- So there are artists, street
artists who, sort of, paint

01:24:17.540 --> 01:24:19.370
and sell as they go.

01:24:19.370 --> 01:24:21.204
And that's also-- that
exists for a purpose.

01:24:21.204 --> 01:24:22.703
And then there's
maybe other artists

01:24:22.703 --> 01:24:24.875
who their whole life they
just sell one concept.

01:24:27.945 --> 01:24:32.220
- OK, great we have
more time for discussion

01:24:32.220 --> 01:24:34.830
downstairs in the reception,
which follows this event.

01:24:34.830 --> 01:24:38.760
So it's just down in the
first floor of this building.

01:24:38.760 --> 01:24:42.310
I want to thank, again,
Joy, Xu Bing, and Eugene.

01:24:42.310 --> 01:24:44.410
Thank you so much, and
thanks to all of you.

